    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Through-the-line (TTL) marketing</strong> is an integrated advertising strategy that combines above-the-line (ATL) mass-reach media — TV, radio, print, outdoor — with below-the-line (BTL) targeted, measurable tactics like email, PPC, direct mail, and in-store promotions. TTL campaigns use both simultaneously so broad awareness drives consideration, and targeted follow-up converts that consideration into action.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">General Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">TTL Advertising, Integrated Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">The terms ATL, BTL, and TTL come from accounting: advertising agencies historically drew a literal line on their billing sheets separating commissionable media buying (above) from non-commissionable direct work (below). Today the line is purely conceptual, but the distinction between mass-reach and targeted advertising remains practically useful for campaign planning.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is TTL marketing?</h2>
        <p>TTL marketing is the practice of running ATL and BTL components of a campaign in a coordinated, integrated way — using the same campaign idea, visual identity, and messaging across both broad-reach and targeted channels. The goal is to close the gap that exists when you run either approach in isolation:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ATL alone</strong> builds broad awareness but struggles to produce measurable direct response. A TV spot makes millions aware but doesn't know who it reached or what they did next.</li>
          <li><strong>BTL alone</strong> converts efficiently within a defined audience but can't scale or build the kind of brand familiarity that lowers customer acquisition cost over time.</li>
          <li><strong>TTL together</strong> uses the ATL layer to build a warm audience, then uses BTL precision to convert that audience at higher rates than cold outreach would achieve.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="atl-btl-ttl">ATL vs BTL vs TTL: the full breakdown</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Channels</th><th>Targeting</th><th>Measurability</th><th>Goal</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>ATL</strong> (Above-the-line)</td>
                <td>TV, radio, print, outdoor, cinema</td>
                <td>Broad demographic</td>
                <td class="cell-meh">Low (reach/frequency only)</td>
                <td>Brand awareness, mass reach</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>BTL</strong> (Below-the-line)</td>
                <td>Email, direct mail, PPC, events, in-store, telemarketing</td>
                <td>Specific segments</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">High (direct response)</td>
                <td>Conversion, loyalty, retention</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>TTL</strong> (Through-the-line)</td>
                <td>All of the above, coordinated</td>
                <td>Both broad and targeted</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Medium-high (mixed attribution)</td>
                <td>Awareness + conversion in one campaign</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How TTL marketing works in practice</h2>
        <p>A TTL campaign typically runs in three coordinated phases:</p>

        <h3>Phase 1: Awareness (ATL layer)</h3>
        <p>Mass-reach media establishes the campaign idea in the broadest possible audience. A TV spot, out-of-home campaign, or sponsored podcast introduces the message and drives initial search volume and brand recall. This phase prioritises reach over precision and is measured in impressions, reach, and frequency.</p>

        <h3>Phase 2: Consideration (TTL bridge)</h3>
        <p>As the ATL campaign runs, digital channels pick up intent signals — search queries, site visits, social engagement — and move warm audiences into more targeted environments. Retargeting ads, branded search campaigns, and social media serve tailored messages to people who responded to the ATL activity. This is the "through" in TTL: the campaign crosses from mass to targeted.</p>

        <h3>Phase 3: Conversion (BTL layer)</h3>
        <p>Email sequences, in-store promotions, direct mail, and sales team outreach close the loop with the most engaged segment of the audience. These tactics are highly measurable and tied directly to revenue outcomes. The BTL layer benefits from the ATL warm-up because the audience already has brand familiarity, which reduces friction and increases response rates.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">The halo effect</div>
          <p>One of the most consistent findings in marketing mix modelling research is that ATL advertising creates a "halo" that improves the performance of BTL channels running simultaneously. When both are live together, email open rates and PPC conversion rates typically improve — because recipients are being primed by the mass-market message at the same time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real TTL marketing campaign examples</h2>

        <h3>Nike — Product launch campaigns</h3>
        <p>Nike's major sneaker launches follow a textbook TTL structure. The ATL layer includes TV spots and billboard takeovers in major markets. Simultaneously, Nike's email list gets early access notifications, the Nike App sends personalised push notifications to users based on past purchase history, and retargeting ads follow users who visited the product page. The coordinated release creates cultural moment (ATL) while precision targeting converts sneaker buyers (BTL).</p>

        <h3>Coca-Cola — Seasonal campaigns</h3>
        <p>Coca-Cola's Christmas campaign runs globally on TV and cinema (ATL) while driving in-store promotions, personalised loyalty programme offers through the Coca-Cola app, and localised social media activations (BTL). The campaign idea is singular — "Share a Coke" or "Holidays are Coming" — but it is executed through every channel simultaneously with channel-appropriate tactics.</p>

        <h3>SaaS brand example</h3>
        <p>A B2B SaaS company runs a TTL campaign around a product launch: podcast sponsorships reach a broad tech audience (ATL), LinkedIn thought leadership posts from the CEO build category awareness (ATL-adjacent), while retargeting campaigns convert visitors from those channels, and sales development reps use intent data from those visits to personalise outreach sequences (BTL). The same core message — "here is why this category matters and why we lead it" — runs through every layer.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for TTL campaigns</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Unify the creative concept first.</strong> TTL campaigns fail when ATL and BTL creative are developed by different teams without coordination. The campaign idea must work at every level of specificity — from a 30-second TV spot to a personalised email to a sales call talking point.</li>
          <li><strong>Sequence the channels intentionally.</strong> The ATL layer should precede the BTL activation by enough time to build awareness but not so long that momentum dies. For major campaigns, ATL typically leads by 1-2 weeks before BTL conversion activity begins.</li>
          <li><strong>Use the BTL data to inform ATL creative.</strong> BTL channels generate real conversion data — what messages, offers, and proof points actually close customers. Feed this back into ATL creative to make mass-reach spend more effective over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Define different success metrics for each layer.</strong> ATL success is measured in brand lift, reach, and share of voice. BTL is measured in conversion rate, CPA, and revenue. Trying to judge an ATL campaign by direct response metrics will lead to wrong conclusions, and vice versa.</li>
          <li><strong>Invest in attribution modelling.</strong> TTL campaigns are difficult to attribute using last-click models because the ATL layer rarely generates the final conversion directly. Marketing mix modelling (MMM) or incremental testing is needed to understand the true contribution of each layer.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common TTL marketing mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Running ATL and BTL in silos.</strong> When the TV team and the email team are not talking, audiences get inconsistent messages that undermine campaign coherence. TTL requires integration, not just co-existence of channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Overspending on ATL without adequate BTL follow-through.</strong> A campaign that creates broad awareness but has no targeted conversion mechanism wastes the ATL investment. Every dollar spent raising awareness should be matched with enough BTL budget to capture the intent that awareness creates.</li>
          <li><strong>Measuring ATL on BTL metrics.</strong> TV reach does not produce immediate click-through rates. Judging ATL by direct response standards leads to premature cuts of brand-building spend that would have compounded positively over time.</li>
          <li><strong>Not adapting creative for each channel.</strong> The same 30-second TV ad should not run verbatim as an email. TTL campaigns require channel-appropriate creative execution of the same core idea — not the same asset in every placement.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="ttl-digital">TTL marketing in the digital era</h2>
        <p>The ATL/BTL/TTL framework was developed for traditional media, but it maps cleanly onto digital channels:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>YouTube pre-rolls and broad social media awareness campaigns function like ATL</li>
          <li>Search retargeting, email marketing, and personalised social ads function like BTL</li>
          <li>A coordinated digital campaign using both in sequence is TTL</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Digital TTL has a significant advantage over traditional TTL: digital ATL channels are far more measurable than TV or print. A YouTube reach campaign can be tracked to site visits, and those site visitors can immediately enter BTL retargeting sequences — creating a tighter feedback loop than was possible with mass media.</p>

